window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : TYPES OF MECHANICAL ENERGY: POTENTIAL ENERGY AND KINETIC ENERGY","question":"You are provided with a retort stand, boss head, clamp, stopwatch, slotted weights, hanger, grooved pulley, thread, measuring tape, and other necessary materials.    (i) Measure and record the radius  R of the pulley.  (ii) Setup the apparatus as illustrated in the diagram above, such that the clamp is 1.5 m above the floor.  (iii) Tie one end of the thread to the pulley.  (iv) Tie the other end of the thread to the hanger.  (v) Slot a mass  m  = 50 g on the hanger.  (vi) Wind the thread around the groove of the pulley until the base of the hanger is at a height  h  = 1.4 m above the floor.  Maintain this height  h for every other value of  m through out the experiment.  (vii) Release the mass to unwind the thread.  (viii) Determine and record the time  t taken by the mass  m to reach the floor.  (ix) Evaluate  t2   (x) Also evaluate a = 2ht2\\frac{2h}{t^{2}}t22h\u200b, T = m1000\\frac{m}{1000}1000m\u200b (10 - a) and  \u03b1 = aR\\frac{a}{R}Ra\u200b  (xi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  m  = 70 g, 90 g, 110 g and 130 g   (xii) Tabulate your readings.  (xiii) Plot a graph with \u03b1 on the vertical axis and  T  on the horizontal axis.  (xiv) Determine the slope  s  , of the graph.  (xv) Evaluate I = Rs\\frac{R}{s}sR\u200b.  (xvi) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"R = 0.08 m    S/N\tm(g)\tt1(s)   t2(s) t = t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)  t2(s2) a = 2ht2\\frac{2h}{t^{2}}t22h\u200b(ms-2)  T = m(10\u2212a)1000\\frac{m\\left(10-a\\right)}{1000}1000m(10\u2212a)\u200b(kgms-2)\u03b1 = aR\\frac{a}{R}Ra\u200b(s-2)1\t50\t1.06\t1.06\t1.06\t1.124\t2.216\t0.389\t27.702\t70\t0.94\t0.94\t0.94\t0.884\t3.583\t0.449\t44.793\t90\t0.90\t0.90\t0.90\t0.810\t4.268\t0.516\t53.354\t110\t0.88\t0.88\t0.88 0.774\t4.674\t0.586\t58.435\t130\t0.86\t0.86\t0.86\t0.740\t5.113\t0.635\t63.91        (xiv) s = \u03b12\u2212\u03b11T2\u2212T1\\frac{\u03b1_{2}-\u03b1_{1}}{T_{2}-T_{1}}T2\u200b\u2212T1\u200b\u03b12\u200b\u2212\u03b11\u200b\u200b = 61.25\u2212300.6\u22120.375\\frac{61.25-30}{0.6-0.375}0.6\u22120.37561.25\u221230\u200b = 31.250.225\\frac{31.25}{0.225}0.22531.25\u200b = 138.89 kg-1m-1    (xv) I = Rs\\frac{R}{s}sR\u200b = 0.08138.89\\frac{0.08}{138.89}138.890.08\u200b = 5.76 &#215; 10-4 kgm2    (xvi)  Precautions:    1. I ensured that the clamp was properly tightened to prevent the apparatus from collapsing during the experiment.    2. I ensured that the pulley was securely mounted and aligned to minimize friction or wobbling during the rotation.    3. I ensured that the thread was free of knots and evenly wound around the pulley groove to avoid irregular motion.    4. I ensured that the thread and hanger setup was not influenced by air currents or external vibrations.    5. I ensured that errors due to parallax on the stopwatch were avoided.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"MOTION : SIMPLE IDEAS OF CIRCULAR MOTION","question":"Define centripetal force","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Centripetal force is the force directed towards the center of a circular path that keeps an object moving in a circular motion.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : TYPES OF MECHANICAL ENERGY: POTENTIAL ENERGY AND KINETIC ENERGY","question":"An object drops to the ground from a height of 2.0 m. Calculate the speed with which it strikes the ground. [g = 10 ms\u22122]    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p e.g 123.123 J/s)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"v2= u2 + 2as    v2= (0)2 + 2 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 2    v2 = 40    v = &radic;40&nbsp;    v = 6.32 ms-1","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a triangular glass prism, four optical pins, and other necessary materials.    (i)  Place the triangular glass prism on a drawing paper and draw its outline  UMR . Remove the prism. Measure and record the value of the angle at  U .   (ii) Draw a normal to the line  UM at  N . Also, draw another line  TN to the normal such that \u03a6 = 60\u00b0. Fix two pins at P1 and P2.  (iii) Replace the prism and x two other pains at P3, and P4, such that the pins appear to be in a straight line with the images of the pins at P1 and P2, when viewed from the side  UR .   (iv) Remove the prism. Join points P2 , and P3, producing the line to meet  TN produced at  Z .   (v) Draw the normal  XY .  (vi) Measure and record the angle of emergence  e and that of deviation  d .  (vii) Repeat the experiment with \u03a6 = 55\u00b0, 50\u00b0, 40\u00b0 and 35\u00b0.  (viii) In each case, measure and record the corresponding values of  e and  d .   (ix) Tabulate your readings.  (x) Plot a graph with  d on the vertical axis and  e  on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0.0) Join your points with a smooth curve.    (xi) From your graph, obtain the minimum deviation  dm and the corresponding angle of emergence  em . Hence, calculate the refractive index n of the prism using the formula: n = sin\u2061(dm+U2)sin\u2061(U2)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(\\frac{d_{m}+U}{2}\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(\\frac{U}{2}\\right)}}sin(2U\u200b)sin(2dm\u200b+U\u200b)\u200b  (xi) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results. Attach your traces to your answer booklet.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"U = 60\u00b0     S/N\t\u03d5 /\u00b0\te/\u00b0\td/\u00b01\t60.0\t38.0\t22.02\t55.0\t42.0\t18.03\t50.0\t45.0\t15.04\t40.0\t50.0\t16.05\t35.0\t53.0\t20.0        (xi) dm = 15.1\u00b0, em = 46.3\u00b0    n = sin\u2061(15.1+602)sin\u2061(602)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(\\frac{15.1+60}{2}\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(\\frac{60}{2}\\right)}}sin(260\u200b)sin(215.1+60\u200b)\u200b    n = sin\u2061(75.12)sin\u2061(30)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(\\frac{75.1}{2}\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(30\\right)}}sin(30)sin(275.1\u200b)\u200b    n = sin\u2061(37.55)sin\u2061(30)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(37.55\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(30\\right)}}sin(30)sin(37.55)\u200b    n = 0.60950.5\\frac{0.6095}{0.5}0.50.6095\u200b    n = 1.22         Precautions:   1. I ensured that neat traces and sharp pencils were used for accurate diagrams.    2. I ensured that pins were reasonably spaced to improve the accuracy of traced paths.    3. I avoided parallax error while reading the protractor to ensure precise measurements.    4. I ensured the triangular prism was properly aligned on the drawing sheet to avoid misalignment errors.    5. I ensured that the protractor was firmly held and correctly positioned when measuring angles.    6. I avoided any external light interference that could distort the observation of refracted rays.    7. I ensured that the experiment setup was stable and not disturbed during measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the conditions necessary for total internal reflection of light to occur.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The conditions necessary for total internal reflection of light to occur are:    1. The light must travel from a denser medium to a less dense medium: The refractive index of the first medium must be greater than that of the second medium.    2. The angle of incidence must be greater than the critical angle: The critical angle is the angle of incidence at which the refracted ray grazes the boundary between the two media, making an angle of 90\u00b0 with the normal. For total internal reflection, the angle of incidence must exceed this value.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"The critical angle for a transparent substance is 39\u00b0. Calculate the refractive index of the substance.    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"c = 39\u00b0    sin c = 1n\\frac{1}{n}n1\u200b    n = 1sin\u2061(c)\\frac{1}{\\sin{\\left(c\\right)}}sin(c)1\u200b    n = 1sin\u2061(39)\\frac{1}{\\sin{\\left(39\\right)}}sin(39)1\u200b    n = 10.6293\\frac{1}{0.6293}0.62931\u200b    n = 1.59","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You have been provided with a resistance box, a voltmeter, a key, a battery, and other necessary materials.  (i) Connect the circuit as shown in the diagram above. With the key  K closed, read and record the voltmeter reading  V0 .  (ii) Set the resistance  R in the resistance box equal to 1 \u03a9.  (iii) Close the key, read and record the potential difference  V on the voltmeter.  (iv) Evaluate  R-1   and  V-1  .  (v) Repeat the procedure for other values or  R  = 2 \u03a9, 3 \u03a9, 4 \u03a9, 5 \u03a9 and 6 \u03a9. Tabulate your readings.  (vi) Plot a graph with  V-1  on the vertical axis and  R-1 on the horizontal axis.  (vii) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph and the intercept,  C , on the vertical axis.  (viii) Evaluate C-1  (ix) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N \tR(\u03a9)      V(V)\tR-1(\u03a9-1)\tV-1(V-1)1\t1.0\t1.26\t1.00\t0.794\t2\t2.0\t1.63\t0.50\t0.613\t3\t3.0\t1.78\t0.33\t0.562\t4\t4.0\t1.90\t0.25\t0.526\t5\t5.0\t1.96\t0.20\t0.510\t6\t6.0\t2.09\t0.17\t0.478        (vii) s = \u2206V\u22121\u2206R\u22121\\frac{\u2206V^{-1}}{\u2206R^{-1}}\u2206R\u22121\u2206V\u22121\u200b = 0.794\u22120.5061\u22120.2\\frac{0.794-0.506}{1-0.2}1\u22120.20.794\u22120.506\u200b = 0.2880.8\\frac{0.288}{0.8}0.80.288\u200b = 0.36 A-1, C = 0.43 V-1    (viii) C-1 = 1C\\frac{1}{C}C1\u200b = 10.43\\frac{1}{0.43}0.431\u200b = 2.33 V     Precautions:      1. I ensured that the key was opened immediately after each reading to prevent the battery from running down quickly.    2. I ensured that all electrical wires were tightly and securely connected to the terminals to avoid current fluctuations.    3. I double-checked all connections to ensure there were no loose or faulty wires that could disrupt the circuit.    4. I ensured that the apparatus was stable and securely positioned to prevent accidental disconnections.    5. I cleaned the battery terminals and wire contacts to ensure efficient current flow.    6. I ensured that the measuring instruments (e.g., ammeter, voltmeter) were properly calibrated before starting the experiment.    7. I handled the apparatus carefully to avoid damaging sensitive components, such as the wires and meters.    8. I repeated each measurement multiple times to ensure consistency and reliability in the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Define the potential difference between two points in an electric circuit.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The potential difference between two points in an electric circuit is the amount of work done to move a unit positive charge from one point to the other. It is measured in volts (V) and mathematically defined as:    V = WQ\\frac{W}{Q}QW\u200b  \u200b  where V is the potential difference, W is the work done (in joules), and Q is the charge (in coulombs).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2015>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2015","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CONCEPTS OF ELECTRIC FIELD, ELECTRIC FIELD INTENSITY (POTENTIAL GRADIENT) AND ELECTRIC POTENTIAL.","question":"Explain why the emf of a cell is greater than the p.d. across the cell when it is supplying current through an external resistance.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The electromotive force (emf) of a cell is greater than the potential difference (p.d.) across the cell when it is supplying current through an external resistance because the internal resistance of the cell opposes the flow of current, causing energy loss as some of the emf is used to overcome this resistance, resulting in a voltage drop inside the cell that reduces the p.d. available across the external circuit.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];